SUMMARY:
The hook passes the raw API response straight through with no normalization. DepositsSection.tsx line 243 reads data?.deposits but the backend returns items — this single line is the root cause of zero rows rendering. No coin→currency or status remapping exists anywhere in the
hook.

FILES:
- path: /algonney/BRIDGE/frontend/front/src/components/adminv2/hooks/useAdminDeposits.ts
- function: useAdminDeposits()
- path: /algonney/BRIDGE/frontend/front/src/components/adminv2/types/index.ts
- function: AdminDepositsResponse, AdminDeposit, DepositStatus
- path: /algonney/BRIDGE/frontend/front/src/components/adminv2/sections/DepositsSection.tsx
- function: DepositsSectionInner

FLOW:
1. useAdminDeposits() calls adminApi.get<AdminDepositsResponse>('/api/v1/admin/deposits?...') (line 32–34)
2. adminApi.get returns the raw parsed JSON — no transformation, no remapping
3. React Query stores the raw object as data
4. DepositsSection.tsx line 243: const deposits = data?.deposits || [];
5. Backend JSON has key items, not deposits → data?.deposits is undefined → falls back to []
6. deposits is always [] → table renders 0 rows regardless of what the backend returned

CODE PROOF:

Hook — raw pass-through, zero normalization (useAdminDeposits.ts lines 20–39):
export function useAdminDeposits(filters: AdminDepositsFilters = {}) {
return useQuery({
queryFn: () => {
// ...builds params...
return adminApi.get<AdminDepositsResponse>( // ← raw response returned as-is
`/api/v1/admin/deposits${queryString ? `?${queryString}` : ''}`
);
},
});
}
No .then(), no select:, no transform — the backend JSON object is returned directly.

Type expects deposits key (types/index.ts line 58–63):
export interface AdminDepositsResponse {
deposits: AdminDeposit[]; // ← expects key named "deposits"
total: number;
page: number;
page_size: number;
}
// Backend actually returns: { items: [...], total: number, has_more: boolean }

The single line causing zero rows (DepositsSection.tsx line 243):
const deposits = data?.deposits || [];
// ^^^^^^^^^
// data is { items: [...], total: N, has_more: bool }
// data.deposits === undefined → fallback to []
// Table always receives an empty array

No coin→currency remapping anywhere in the hook. AdminDeposit.currency (types line 48) will be undefined for every row because backend sends field named coin.

No status remapping anywhere in the hook. Backend emits credited, confirmed, below_minimum, manual_review — none are transformed before reaching statusVariantMap.

FINDINGS:
- The hook does zero normalization — it is a pure pass-through wrapper around adminApi.get
- data?.deposits (DepositsSection line 243) is the single exact line that causes 0 rows — deposits key does not exist on the backend response object
- AdminDepositsResponse.deposits (types line 59) is the type-level declaration of the wrong key
- AdminDeposit.currency (types line 48) will always be undefined at runtime because backend field is coin
- DepositStatus union (types line 41) contains phantom approved and omits confirmed, credited, below_minimum, manual_review
- usePendingDepositsCount() (hook line 57–68) also calls response.total — this part works because total key name matches; however it sends ?status=pending which happens to be a valid backend value, so the count itself is not broken

LIKELY_BREAKPOINTS:
- DepositsSection.tsx line 243: data?.deposits — primary zero-rows breakpoint
- types/index.ts line 59: deposits: in AdminDepositsResponse — type-level root of the key mismatch
- types/index.ts line 48: currency: in AdminDeposit — causes blank currency column
- types/index.ts line 41: DepositStatus union — causes undefined badge variants for 4 real statuses
- DepositsSection.tsx line 307: data={deposits} — receives [] always, so table is always empty

RECOMMENDED_NEXT_CHECK:
- Read adminApi.ts get() method to confirm it returns response.data or the raw parsed body directly (to rule out any axios/fetch wrapper that might itself remap keys before the hook sees the response)
